become more challenging,

00:34:14.540 --> 00:34:17.710 align:middle line:84%
there's a huge and rising
hunger on the part of just about

00:34:17.710 --> 00:34:21.699 align:middle line:84%
everybody to reconnect with
what gives us authentic meaning

00:34:21.699 --> 00:34:23.260 align:middle line:90%
and purpose.

00:34:23.260 --> 00:34:26.139 align:middle line:84%
Through an extensive study
of diverse transformational

00:34:26.139 --> 00:34:30.310 align:middle line:84%
paths and practices summarized
in our book, "Living Deeply--

00:34:30.310 --> 00:34:33.130 align:middle line:84%
the Art and Science
of Transformation,"

00:34:33.130 --> 00:34:37.000 align:middle line:84%
we've learned an important key
to your own human flourishing

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:40.840 align:middle line:84%
can be as simple as shifting
your perspective from what

00:34:40.840 --> 00:34:43.480 align:middle line:84%
doesn't work in your
life to that which

00:34:43.480 --> 00:34:46.540 align:middle line:90%
makes you full and complete.

00:34:46.540 --> 00:34:49.690 align:middle line:84%
Through various transformative
traditions, both ancient

00:34:49.690 --> 00:34:53.800 align:middle line:84%
and modern, we've identified
diverse practices,

00:34:53.800 --> 00:34:57.790 align:middle line:84%
each of which can provide
gateways into living deeply.

00:34:57.790 --> 00:35:01.450 align:middle line:84%
This DVD program is directed
to helping you find ways

00:35:01.450 --> 00:35:04.900 align:middle line:84%
that you can add greater
richness, meaning, depth,

00:35:04.900 --> 00:35:08.880 align:middle line:84%
and joy to every
moment of your life.

00:35:08.880 --> 00:35:12.540 align:middle line:84%
Through a series of short
transformative practices led

00:35:12.540 --> 00:35:15.670 align:middle line:84%
by wisdom-keepers from
different cultural, religious,

00:35:15.670 --> 00:35:17.670 align:middle line:84%
and spiritual
traditions, you may

00:35:17.670 --> 00:35:21.550 align:middle line:84%
learn some new ways in which
to cultivate peace, love,

00:35:21.550 --> 00:35:25.230 align:middle line:84%
forgiveness, gratefulness,
and a deep sense of connection

00:35:25.230 --> 00:35:27.380 align:middle line:90%
to a greater whole.

00:35:27.380 --> 00:35:30.800 align:middle line:84%
No matter who you are
or where you come from,

00:35:30.800 --> 00:35:34.010 align:middle line:84%
whether you seek to transform
your life completely

00:35:34.010 --> 00:35:35.960 align:middle line:84%
or to simply make
adjustments that

00:35:35.960 --> 00:35:40.220 align:middle line:84%
will add a layer of richness
to your everyday experiences,

00:35:40.220 --> 00:35:42.410 align:middle line:84%
We hope that you'll
find something valuable

00:35:42.410 --> 00:35:44.840 align:middle line:84%
in this collection of
practices from some

00:35:44.840 --> 00:35:47.750 align:middle line:90%
of the world's wisdom-keepers.

00:35:47.750 --> 00:35:49.970 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So what are some
of your daily practices

00:35:49.970 --> 00:35:51.260 align:middle line:90%
that you live by?

00:35:51.260 --> 00:35:53.468 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: One of the things
I think that's important

00:35:53.468 --> 00:35:57.080 align:middle line:84%
is, as you have
engaged in a practice,

00:35:57.080 --> 00:36:01.480 align:middle line:84%
moving off the cushion or
out of the pew and into life.

00:36:01.480 --> 00:36:03.770 align:middle line:90%
So life becomes the practice.

00:36:03.770 --> 00:36:06.655 align:middle line:84%
And that means every
moment with every person,

00:36:06.655 --> 00:36:07.780 align:middle line:90%
even those people who can--

00:36:07.780 --> 00:36:08.420 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Every challenge.

00:36:08.420 --> 00:36:08.990 align:middle line:90%
>>SCHLITZ: Yes.

00:36:08.990 --> 00:36:10.910 align:middle line:84%
Those people who can
push every button we

00:36:10.910 --> 00:36:13.370 align:middle line:84%
have become our
greatest teachers.

00:36:13.370 --> 00:36:15.980 align:middle line:84%
So bringing that kind
of loving kindness

00:36:15.980 --> 00:36:19.430 align:middle line:84%
to the ticket taker at the
tollbooth, or the person

00:36:19.430 --> 00:36:22.550 align:middle line:84%
at the cashier counter
in the grocery store,

00:36:22.550 --> 00:36:26.240 align:middle line:84%
become people for us to
engage in and recognize

00:36:26.240 --> 00:36:28.520 align:middle line:90%
our common humanity with.

00:36:28.520 --> 00:36:31.040 align:middle line:84%
Gratitude is really
my favorite practice.

00:36:31.040 --> 00:36:35.870 align:middle line:84%
And I do loving kindness
meditation every day,

00:36:35.870 --> 00:36:38.540 align:middle line:84%
pretty much many
times during the day,

00:36:38.540 --> 00:36:42.000 align:middle line:84%
and especially in
difficult situations.

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:43.827 align:middle line:84%
I had-- Brother
David Steindl-Rast

00:36:43.827 --> 00:36:45.410 align:middle line:84%
was one of the
teachers we interviewed

00:36:45.410 --> 00:36:46.400 align:middle line:90%
for "Living Deeply."

00:36:46.400 --> 00:36:49.610 align:middle line:84%
And he talks about how
it's easy to be grateful

00:36:49.610 --> 00:36:51.820 align:middle line:90%
when everything's going well.

00:36:51.820 --> 00:36:53.180 align:middle line:90%
But what if you're challenged?

00:36:53.180 --> 00:36:55.130 align:middle line:84%
What if you're in
the middle of a war?

00:36:55.130 --> 00:36:59.120 align:middle line:84%
Or what if somebody is
perpetrating genocide?

00:36:59.120 --> 00:37:00.470 align:middle line:90%
What do you do with that?

00:37:00.470 --> 00:37:02.510 align:middle line:84%
And how do you
cultivate your gratitude

00:37:02.510 --> 00:37:06.050 align:middle line:84%
for whatever you have to
learn from that person?

00:37:06.050 --> 00:37:07.490 align:middle line:90%
And so those are the teachings.

00:37:07.490 --> 00:37:09.460 align:middle line:90%
They're not always easy.

00:37:09.460 --> 00:37:12.330 align:middle line:84%
I don't mean to trivialize
it, because they're not always

00:37:12.330 --> 00:37:13.130 align:middle line:90%
easy.

00:37:13.130 --> 00:37:15.530 align:middle line:10%
But I think the more
we can practice,

00:37:15.530 --> 00:37:19.587 align:middle line:10%
the more they become the habits
and really the easier they get.

00:37:19.587 --> 00:37:20.420 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Fascinating.

00:37:20.420 --> 00:37:21.385 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, true.

00:37:21.385 --> 00:37:23.510 align:middle line:84%
And you never know it when
you're going through it.

00:37:23.510 --> 00:37:25.565 align:middle line:84%
But then at the end or
on the other side of it,

00:37:25.565 --> 00:37:29.840 align:middle line:84%
it makes sense if you
have that practice.

00:37:29.840 --> 00:37:32.090 align:middle line:84%
You were inspired by
someone in the movie,

00:37:32.090 --> 00:37:33.690 align:middle line:84%
and it changed
your view on death.

00:37:33.690 --> 00:37:37.730 align:middle line:84%
Can you tell us a little about
that, the Lakota tribe member.

00:37:37.730 --> 00:37:40.220 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: Oh, well,
there were so many people.

00:37:40.220 --> 00:37:42.800 align:middle line:84%
I really had the privilege
of interviewing folks

00:37:42.800 --> 00:37:45.110 align:middle line:90%
from many different traditions.

00:37:45.110 --> 00:37:49.760 align:middle line:84%
In the indigenous traditions,
there isn't this separation.

00:37:49.760 --> 00:37:56.880 align:middle line:84%
The model of objectivity is less
reified in indigenous culture.

00:37:56.880 --> 00:38:01.010 align:middle line:84%
So there isn't this sense
that that tree over there

00:38:01.010 --> 00:38:03.260 align:middle line:90%
is detached from me.

00:38:03.260 --> 00:38:06.740 align:middle line:84%
There is this sense that
we are a living system,

00:38:06.740 --> 00:38:10.580 align:middle line:84%
and that that tree has
consciousness and awareness,

00:38:10.580 --> 00:38:15.050 align:middle line:84%
and that it is my responsibility
to connect to that.

00:38:15.050 --> 00:38:17.750 align:middle line:84%
And so one of the
travesties, I think,

00:38:17.750 --> 00:38:21.290 align:middle line:84%
of the dominant scientific
Western worldview

00:38:21.290 --> 00:38:25.580 align:middle line:84%
is this idea of objectivity,
that the only valid truth

00:38:25.580 --> 00:38:27.020 align:middle line:90%
is out there.

00:38:27.020 --> 00:38:30.980 align:middle line:84%
Because once we can begin to
shift that and transform that,

00:38:30.980 --> 00:38:35.270 align:middle line:84%
we become much more
responsible, and we recognize

00:38:35.270 --> 00:38:37.670 align:middle line:90%
our interconnectedness.

00:38:37.670 --> 00:38:42.230 align:middle line:90%
I also interviewed Satish Kumar.

00:38:42.230 --> 00:38:45.620 align:middle line:90%
He is of the Jain tradition.

00:38:45.620 --> 00:38:52.100 align:middle line:84%
And he's somebody who practices
forgiveness, loving kindness,

00:38:52.100 --> 00:38:55.190 align:middle line:84%
he has devoted his
life to service.

00:38:55.190 --> 00:39:00.680 align:middle line:84%
And his mother, on her
deathbed, was in India,

00:39:00.680 --> 00:39:03.140 align:middle line:84%
and she was surrounded
by loved ones,

00:39:03.140 --> 00:39:06.380 align:middle line:84%
and oftentimes we
find that people

00:39:06.380 --> 00:39:08.190 align:middle line:90%
don't want to let you go.

00:39:08.190 --> 00:39:11.780 align:middle line:84%
And that isn't really about
the person transitioning,

00:39:11.780 --> 00:39:15.270 align:middle line:84%
it's really much more about
our fear of losing them.

00:39:15.270 --> 00:39:22.040 align:middle line:84%
And she just said go away,
I'm fine, and I am ready.

00:39:22.040 --> 00:39:26.580 align:middle line:84%
And so it's these
people who have no fear

00:39:26.580 --> 00:39:31.760 align:middle line:84%
and who also have that
sense of love and service,

00:39:31.760 --> 00:39:37.370 align:middle line:84%
that will take them,
their sense of altruism

00:39:37.370 --> 00:39:39.710 align:middle line:90%
to something beyond themself.

00:39:39.710 --> 00:39:41.060 align:middle line:90%
So those are great.

00:39:41.060 --> 00:39:42.770 align:middle line:84%
I also really
appreciated some of

00:39:42.770 --> 00:39:45.700 align:middle line:90%
the evidence-based approaches.

00:39:45.700 --> 00:39:47.450 align:middle line:84%
You know, I think we're
moving into a kind

00:39:47.450 --> 00:39:49.700 align:middle line:84%
of an evidence-based
spirituality.

00:39:49.700 --> 00:39:50.660 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What's that?

00:39:50.660 --> 00:39:52.520 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: Well,
maybe I made it up.

00:39:52.520 --> 00:39:52.780 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:39:52.780 --> 00:39:53.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I love it.

00:39:53.330 --> 00:39:54.200 align:middle line:90%
I love it, yeah.

00:39:54.200 --> 00:39:56.200 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: But I do think
that-- a lot of people

00:39:56.200 --> 00:39:59.330 align:middle line:84%
talk about using
quantum physics,

00:39:59.330 --> 00:40:00.853 align:middle line:84%
either literally
or as a metaphor--

00:40:00.853 --> 00:40:02.270 align:middle line:84%
it should be
metaphorical, really.

00:40:02.270 --> 00:40:08.660 align:middle line:84%
But we want science somehow
to support and calibrate

00:40:08.660 --> 00:40:13.910 align:middle line:84%
what these mystical or
noetic experiences might be.

00:40:13.910 --> 00:40:15.530 align:middle line:84%
So I interviewed a
lot of people who

00:40:15.530 --> 00:40:19.400 align:middle line:84%
had studied near-death,
out-of-body, reincarnation,

00:40:19.400 --> 00:40:20.810 align:middle line:90%
mediumship.

00:40:20.810 --> 00:40:24.020 align:middle line:84%
And one of the most
interesting things,

00:40:24.020 --> 00:40:26.450 align:middle line:84%
I think, from an
evidential point of view,

00:40:26.450 --> 00:40:29.780 align:middle line:84%
is the work that was started by
Ian Stevenson, a psychiatrist

00:40:29.780 --> 00:40:32.210 align:middle line:84%
at the University of
Virginia, and picked up

00:40:32.210 --> 00:40:34.940 align:middle line:84%
by a remarkable team
of scientists there.

00:40:34.940 --> 00:40:38.420 align:middle line:84%
Jim Tucker was somebody I
interviewed for the film.

00:40:38.420 --> 00:40:44.960 align:middle line:84%
And he described one particular
incident where this young

00:40:44.960 --> 00:40:49.340 align:middle line:84%
child, 2, 3 years old-- he
was old enough to talk--

00:40:49.340 --> 00:40:52.380 align:middle line:90%
remembered a past life.

00:40:52.380 --> 00:40:54.670 align:middle line:84%
And he would tell
his father, you know,

00:40:54.670 --> 00:40:57.410 align:middle line:84%
it used to be me
changing your diapers.

00:40:57.410 --> 00:41:01.490 align:middle line:84%
And he said, you know, I used
to have this car that looked

00:41:01.490 --> 00:41:03.770 align:middle line:90%
like a certain type of car.

00:41:03.770 --> 00:41:05.820 align:middle line:84%
And they ended up
finding some pictures,

00:41:05.820 --> 00:41:08.320 align:middle line:84%
they laid them all out on the
table, and he said, that's it,

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:09.260 align:middle line:90%
that's my car.

00:41:09.260 --> 00:41:11.330 align:middle line:84%
And then they showed
a graduation picture

00:41:11.330 --> 00:41:13.010 align:middle line:90%
from elementary school.

00:41:13.010 --> 00:41:15.570 align:middle line:84%
And he's like, there
I am, right there.

00:41:15.570 --> 00:41:16.370 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:41:16.370 --> 00:41:18.912 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: And one of the things
that Stevenson did in a very

00:41:18.912 --> 00:41:19.970 align:middle line:90%
rigorous fashion--

00:41:19.970 --> 00:41:24.050 align:middle line:84%
because science is good, science
has very great qualities--

00:41:24.050 --> 00:41:27.440 align:middle line:84%
is to have this
sense of discernment.

00:41:27.440 --> 00:41:29.420 align:middle line:84%
And so what
Stevenson tried to do

00:41:29.420 --> 00:41:33.600 align:middle line:84%
is find evidence
of reincarnation.

00:41:33.600 --> 00:41:37.730 align:middle line:84%
But in particular, he
amassed a body of stories,

00:41:37.730 --> 00:41:41.630 align:middle line:84%
really, about people who
remembered a past life and who

00:41:41.630 --> 00:41:44.420 align:middle line:84%
had some kind of
biological marker

00:41:44.420 --> 00:41:48.350 align:middle line:84%
that supported the cause of
death in the previous life.

00:41:48.350 --> 00:41:54.120 align:middle line:84%
So for example, this child
had a scar, here and here.

00:41:54.120 --> 00:41:57.020 align:middle line:84%
Well, it turns out they
were able to, putting

00:41:57.020 --> 00:41:59.930 align:middle line:84%
the pieces together,
find a person who

00:41:59.930 --> 00:42:03.890 align:middle line:84%
matched this young
child experience who

00:42:03.890 --> 00:42:06.350 align:middle line:84%
had died from a gunshot
wound in the head.

00:42:06.350 --> 00:42:09.000 align:middle line:84%
And the gunshot had gone in
one side and out the other.

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:09.800 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:42:09.800 --> 00:42:12.350 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: So suddenly
you're bringing together

00:42:12.350 --> 00:42:17.090 align:middle line:84%
what is an ancient religious
belief in reincarnation

00:42:17.090 --> 00:42:18.800 align:middle line:84%
with this kind of
discernment that

00:42:18.800 --> 00:42:22.220 align:middle line:84%
comes from Western science
and that critical mind.

00:42:22.220 --> 00:42:24.830 align:middle line:84%
And there are
hundreds and hundreds

00:42:24.830 --> 00:42:26.990 align:middle line:84%
of these stories that
have been well-documented.

00:42:26.990 --> 00:42:28.640 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Scientific spirituality.

00:42:28.640 --> 00:42:31.040 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: Exactly, and
evidence-based spirituality.

00:42:31.040 --> 00:42:33.950 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's kind of
what mediumship is as well.

00:42:33.950 --> 00:42:37.310 align:middle line:84%
I mean, some of these
incredible mediums

00:42:37.310 --> 00:42:41.570 align:middle line:84%
are so gifted to have the
evidential side come up.

00:42:41.570 --> 00:42:42.370 align:middle line:90%
It's amazing.

00:42:42.370 --> 00:42:43.328 align:middle line:90%
>>SCHLITZ: That's true.

00:42:43.328 --> 00:42:45.350 align:middle line:84%
We talked to some people
who were doing research

00:42:45.350 --> 00:42:47.300 align:middle line:90%
on mediumship.

00:42:47.300 --> 00:42:49.070 align:middle line:84%
One of the stories
I like the best

00:42:49.070 --> 00:42:51.620 align:middle line:84%
is my colleague,
Arnaud Delorme--

00:42:51.620 --> 00:42:55.880 align:middle line:84%
he's a psychophysiologist,
so he's

00:42:55.880 --> 00:42:59.150 align:middle line:84%
pretty deep into the
Western scientific model--

00:42:59.150 --> 00:43:02.270 align:middle line:84%
and he did this
study with mediums.

00:43:02.270 --> 00:43:05.540 align:middle line:84%
They brought them into
the lab, and then you

00:43:05.540 --> 00:43:06.970 align:middle line:90%
would be a sitter, for example.

00:43:06.970 --> 00:43:09.230 align:middle line:84%
So you would have a
question about somebody

00:43:09.230 --> 00:43:11.540 align:middle line:90%
that had passed on.

00:43:11.540 --> 00:43:16.100 align:middle line:84%
And so you knew who that person
was, and you had qualities.

00:43:16.100 --> 00:43:20.510 align:middle line:84%
So the medium would tell
you about your experience,

00:43:20.510 --> 00:43:22.820 align:middle line:84%
and then you, line
by line, would

00:43:22.820 --> 00:43:28.070 align:middle line:84%
evaluate how much the
medium's transmission matched

00:43:28.070 --> 00:43:29.690 align:middle line:90%
your experience of this person.

00:43:29.690 --> 00:43:30.490 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:43:30.490 --> 00:43:31.940 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: So you
could validate,

00:43:31.940 --> 00:43:35.233 align:middle line:84%
yes, this worked, this
worked, this didn't work.

00:43:35.233 --> 00:43:36.650 align:middle line:84%
And what they were
able to do then

00:43:36.650 --> 00:43:40.880 align:middle line:84%
is look at the
psychophysiology of the medium

00:43:40.880 --> 00:43:43.340 align:middle line:84%
during the correct
readings as compared

00:43:43.340 --> 00:43:45.380 align:middle line:90%
to the incorrect readings.

00:43:45.380 --> 00:43:48.500 align:middle line:84%
And they found that there
were significant differences

00:43:48.500 --> 00:43:51.510 align:middle line:84%
in the memory storage
part of the brain.

00:43:51.510 --> 00:43:53.210 align:middle line:84%
So in other words,
when the person

00:43:53.210 --> 00:43:58.790 align:middle line:84%
was getting correct information
about your departed loved one,

00:43:58.790 --> 00:44:03.680 align:middle line:84%
it's almost as though the mind
clears out and creates a space

00:44:03.680 --> 00:44:05.280 align:middle line:90%
for other memory to come in.

00:44:05.280 --> 00:44:06.080 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:44:06.080 --> 00:44:07.997 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: Now, this has
yet to be replicated.

00:44:07.997 --> 00:44:09.110 align:middle line:90%
It needs that.

00:44:09.110 --> 00:44:12.650 align:middle line:84%
But it's something that I
think is extremely provocative,

00:44:12.650 --> 00:44:17.665 align:middle line:84%
and again shows the marriage
of these two worldviews.

00:44:17.665 --> 00:44:19.040 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's like
remote viewing.

00:44:19.040 --> 00:44:21.620 align:middle line:84%
I mean, they have,
over and over again,

00:44:21.620 --> 00:44:23.970 align:middle line:90%
found and proved that works.

00:44:23.970 --> 00:44:24.830 align:middle line:90%
>>SCHLITZ: Right.

00:44:24.830 --> 00:44:28.820 align:middle line:84%
It's, again, an example,
that our consciousness

00:44:28.820 --> 00:44:33.500 align:middle line:84%
in all likelihood has these
capacities to reach out

00:44:33.500 --> 00:44:35.810 align:middle line:90%
into the world or the universe.

00:44:35.810 --> 00:44:37.370 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, it
makes you question,

00:44:37.370 --> 00:44:40.760 align:middle line:90%
is there a life after life?

00:44:40.760 --> 00:44:44.660 align:middle line:84%
And if there are all
these evidential mediums

00:44:44.660 --> 00:44:49.020 align:middle line:84%
or remote viewers tapping
in, yeah, there could be.

00:44:49.020 --> 00:44:51.290 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: My
thing is to prepare

00:44:51.290 --> 00:44:54.770 align:middle line:84%
myself to get to a black
hole and out the other side.

00:44:54.770 --> 00:44:56.440 align:middle line:90%
[BOTH CHUCKLING]

00:44:56.440 --> 00:44:57.655 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Never come back.

00:44:57.655 --> 00:45:00.530 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: Well, or come
back to something else.

00:45:00.530 --> 00:45:04.670 align:middle line:84%
I do think we've been lost in
our three-dimensional reality.

00:45:04.670 --> 00:45:07.970 align:middle line:84%
And we know, from
mathematics and physics,

00:45:07.970 --> 00:45:11.030 align:middle line:84%
that there are multiple
dimensions that are possible,

00:45:11.030 --> 00:45:12.620 align:middle line:90%
certainly, mathematically.

00:45:12.620 --> 00:45:15.110 align:middle line:84%
And these black holes
remain mysterious.

00:45:15.110 --> 00:45:19.040 align:middle line:84%
What happens if we go through
and end up somewhere else--

00:45:19.040 --> 00:45:19.840 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:45:19.840 --> 00:45:20.757 align:middle line:90%
>>SCHLITZ: --entirely?

00:45:20.757 --> 00:45:21.710 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Very possible.

00:45:21.710 --> 00:45:23.030 align:middle line:90%
Very possible.

00:45:23.030 --> 00:45:25.640 align:middle line:84%
So would you say that
this new worldview

00:45:25.640 --> 00:45:27.950 align:middle line:84%
is kind of emerging
between science,

00:45:27.950 --> 00:45:31.370 align:middle line:84%
and spirituality, and
different world cultures.

00:45:31.370 --> 00:45:34.400 align:middle line:84%
Would you say that it's
emerging in a way that

00:45:34.400 --> 00:45:41.270 align:middle line:84%
can create something that is
digestible for the mainstream?

00:45:41.270 --> 00:45:46.190 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: I think most people
have a belief that transcends

00:45:46.190 --> 00:45:47.990 align:middle line:90%
reductionist science.

00:45:47.990 --> 00:45:52.010 align:middle line:84%
So I don't think it's a
huge leap for most people

00:45:52.010 --> 00:45:57.740 align:middle line:84%
to think that we have
alternative worlds

00:45:57.740 --> 00:46:01.610 align:middle line:84%
or that there may be
spirits or angels.

00:46:01.610 --> 00:46:07.940 align:middle line:84%
Many cultures believe in
alternative forms of life.

00:46:07.940 --> 00:46:10.230 align:middle line:84%
You think about
people in the Amazon.

00:46:10.230 --> 00:46:12.930 align:middle line:84%
And when they go
to sleep at night,

00:46:12.930 --> 00:46:14.750 align:middle line:84%
they believe that
the soul leaves

00:46:14.750 --> 00:46:19.250 align:middle line:84%
the body, travels into the
spirit realm, comes back.

00:46:19.250 --> 00:46:24.080 align:middle line:84%
And they do this dream-sharing
practice, where every morning,

00:46:24.080 --> 00:46:26.960 align:middle line:84%
they feel it is their
social responsibility

00:46:26.960 --> 00:46:29.420 align:middle line:84%
to report the content
of their dreams.

00:46:29.420 --> 00:46:32.540 align:middle line:84%
Because nobody dreams
just for the individual,

00:46:32.540 --> 00:46:34.920 align:middle line:84%
they dream for the
good of the group.

00:46:34.920 --> 00:46:37.830 align:middle line:84%
And so you think about,
well, what's happening there?

00:46:37.830 --> 00:46:39.340 align:middle line:90%
They are going out somehow.

00:46:39.340 --> 00:46:40.910 align:middle line:84%
And like we would
read the newspaper

00:46:40.910 --> 00:46:45.260 align:middle line:84%
to see what happened while we
were sleeping, they come in

00:46:45.260 --> 00:46:48.170 align:middle line:84%
and they download
what they experienced,

00:46:48.170 --> 00:46:49.550 align:middle line:90%
and then they use that.

00:46:49.550 --> 00:46:53.480 align:middle line:84%
It's a very utilitarian kind
of concept, where they then

00:46:53.480 --> 00:46:55.940 align:middle line:84%
decide, will we
be visited today,

00:46:55.940 --> 00:47:00.600 align:middle line:84%
will the visitors be friendly,
where should we go hunting.

00:47:00.600 --> 00:47:03.740 align:middle line:84%
These kinds of things
become very acceptable

00:47:03.740 --> 00:47:04.670 align:middle line:90%
in that worldview.

00:47:04.670 --> 00:47:08.060 align:middle line:84%
And most indigenous
cultures have that.

00:47:08.060 --> 00:47:12.778 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's in a way easier
to do in an indigenous culture.

00:47:12.778 --> 00:47:15.320 align:middle line:84%
Think about doing that living
in New York City, where there's

00:47:15.320 --> 00:47:18.110 align:middle line:84%
all these different elements
coming at you in various times

00:47:18.110 --> 00:47:19.370 align:middle line:90%
during the day.

00:47:19.370 --> 00:47:23.850 align:middle line:84%
To hold onto that is
easier in an environment

00:47:23.850 --> 00:47:25.190 align:middle line:90%
that it's a little less chaotic.

00:47:25.190 --> 00:47:26.190 align:middle line:90%
Do you know what I mean?

00:47:26.190 --> 00:47:26.990 align:middle line:90%
>>SCHLITZ: Yeah.

00:47:26.990 --> 00:47:28.907 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Can I ask you
about honoring the dead?

00:47:28.907 --> 00:47:29.750 align:middle line:90%
>>SCHLITZ: Mm-hmm.

00:47:29.750 --> 00:47:32.000 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And there's
many cultures that do.

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:35.390 align:middle line:84%
And even bring back the
dead on the Day of the Dead.

00:47:35.390 --> 00:47:38.150 align:middle line:84%
There's so many different
ways to experience.

00:47:38.150 --> 00:47:42.830 align:middle line:84%
What do you think we do as a
culture in America as opposed

00:47:42.830 --> 00:47:44.930 align:middle line:90%
to the rest of the world?

00:47:44.930 --> 00:47:47.443 align:middle line:90%
Is there an imbalance there?

00:47:47.443 --> 00:47:49.610 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: Again, I think
it's very individualistic.

00:47:49.610 --> 00:47:53.390 align:middle line:84%
I don't know that we
have as much freedom

00:47:53.390 --> 00:47:55.850 align:middle line:84%
to express our emotions
at the moment of death.

00:47:55.850 --> 00:47:57.980 align:middle line:84%
I think there's a
lot of restraint

00:47:57.980 --> 00:48:04.550 align:middle line:84%
that is put on people if they
have an outburst of emotion.

00:48:04.550 --> 00:48:07.635 align:middle line:84%
That's kind of discouraged a lot
in our Western culture, which

00:48:07.635 --> 00:48:09.260 align:middle line:84%
I think is a shame,
because people need

00:48:09.260 --> 00:48:11.720 align:middle line:90%
to express in whatever way.

00:48:11.720 --> 00:48:15.770 align:middle line:84%
But you do think now,
there is no one culture.

00:48:15.770 --> 00:48:20.420 align:middle line:84%
And we are a conglomeration
of many traditions.

00:48:20.420 --> 00:48:24.530 align:middle line:84%
So in California, where I
live, the Day of the Dead

00:48:24.530 --> 00:48:29.340 align:middle line:84%
is considered a very common
and encouraged practice.

00:48:29.340 --> 00:48:32.000 align:middle line:84%
So you'll find
storefronts with altars,

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:33.920 align:middle line:90%
all up and down the street.

00:48:33.920 --> 00:48:37.370 align:middle line:10%
And you'll find that
for a good month,

00:48:37.370 --> 00:48:41.960 align:middle line:10%
people are participating in
various things that connect

00:48:41.960 --> 00:48:43.950 align:middle line:10%
them to the departed loved one.

00:48:43.950 --> 00:48:46.640 align:middle line:84%
It comes out of
ancient paganism,

00:48:46.640 --> 00:48:50.120 align:middle line:84%
where it was thought that,
at this time of the year,

00:48:50.120 --> 00:48:52.970 align:middle line:84%
in the fall, around
the Halloween

00:48:52.970 --> 00:48:57.860 align:middle line:84%
time, that the veil between the
living in the dead was thin.

00:48:57.860 --> 00:49:01.350 align:middle line:84%
And so it was kind of
a permeable membrane.

00:49:01.350 --> 00:49:04.590 align:middle line:84%
And it isn't all
about loving the dead,

00:49:04.590 --> 00:49:07.190 align:middle line:84%
it's also about appeasing
the dead so that they

00:49:07.190 --> 00:49:09.120 align:middle line:90%
don't do tricks on you.

00:49:09.120 --> 00:49:11.000 align:middle line:84%
So you want to make
sure that they're

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:14.720 align:middle line:84%
happy and taken care of so that
they don't try to undermine

00:49:14.720 --> 00:49:15.930 align:middle line:90%
you and become mischievous.

00:49:15.930 --> 00:49:17.630 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: The underworld.

00:49:17.630 --> 00:49:18.600 align:middle line:90%
>>SCHLITZ: Or whatever.

00:49:18.600 --> 00:49:20.150 align:middle line:84%
They have different--
again, there's

00:49:20.150 --> 00:49:24.080 align:middle line:84%
different models
in that culture.

00:49:24.080 --> 00:49:29.510 align:middle line:84%
You would see a parallel
world where, for example, if--

00:49:29.510 --> 00:49:31.640 align:middle line:84%
during this time of
the Day of the Dead--

00:49:31.640 --> 00:49:34.070 align:middle line:84%
the person had
been a hairdresser,

00:49:34.070 --> 00:49:36.500 align:middle line:90%
you might give them something--

00:49:36.500 --> 00:49:39.410 align:middle line:84%
it could even be a paper
something that you could burn--

00:49:39.410 --> 00:49:44.010 align:middle line:84%
that supports them in the other
world at a parallel level.

00:49:44.010 --> 00:49:44.810 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:49:44.810 --> 00:49:47.970 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: So they're doing
basically the same thing there,

00:49:47.970 --> 00:49:50.600 align:middle line:84%
but they're doing it in
a non-physical manner.

00:49:50.600 --> 00:49:52.850 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So they're honoring
the dead and gifting.

00:49:52.850 --> 00:49:53.758 align:middle line:90%
>>SCHLITZ: Yeah.

00:49:53.758 --> 00:49:54.800 align:middle line:90%
And celebrating the dead.

00:49:54.800 --> 00:49:56.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And celebrating.

00:49:56.330 --> 00:49:57.830 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: It's a
very joyful thing.

00:49:57.830 --> 00:50:00.540 align:middle line:84%
Participating in one of
the parades, for example,

00:50:00.540 --> 00:50:04.730 align:middle line:84%
you'll have the mariachis
singing, and performing,

00:50:04.730 --> 00:50:08.540 align:middle line:84%
and people wearing costumes
and dressed up like skeletons.

00:50:08.540 --> 00:50:11.603 align:middle line:84%
And it makes it much
more accessible.

00:50:11.603 --> 00:50:13.520 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: There was a great
movie called "Coco."

00:50:13.520 --> 00:50:16.760 align:middle line:84%
And it was a great movie,
and it was about that.

00:50:16.760 --> 00:50:18.530 align:middle line:84%
And basically the
message of the movie

00:50:18.530 --> 00:50:22.670 align:middle line:84%
was if you honor and remember
those who have passed,

00:50:22.670 --> 00:50:25.490 align:middle line:90%
it keeps their memory stronger.

00:50:25.490 --> 00:50:26.340 align:middle line:90%
And it's true.

00:50:26.340 --> 00:50:28.920 align:middle line:84%
If you forget, their
memories fades.

00:50:28.920 --> 00:50:30.300 align:middle line:90%
>>SCHLITZ: Right.

00:50:30.300 --> 00:50:33.580 align:middle line:90%
And that's one domain of it.

00:50:33.580 --> 00:50:37.260 align:middle line:84%
So that's the idea that
we hold these memories

00:50:37.260 --> 00:50:39.490 align:middle line:90%
and we can keep them alive.

00:50:39.490 --> 00:50:41.250 align:middle line:84%
But there is also
the idea that there's

00:50:41.250 --> 00:50:43.440 align:middle line:90%
something more than a memory.

00:50:43.440 --> 00:50:45.870 align:middle line:90%
It's actually a being.

00:50:45.870 --> 00:50:49.380 align:middle line:84%
It is a metaphysical
force that still

00:50:49.380 --> 00:50:52.687 align:middle line:90%
exists in some parallel place.

00:50:52.687 --> 00:50:55.020 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: This whole-- I love
this, because we're actually

00:50:55.020 --> 00:50:57.030 align:middle line:84%
honoring the dead
when we're talking

00:50:57.030 --> 00:50:58.740 align:middle line:90%
about it, which is great.

00:50:58.740 --> 00:51:02.160 align:middle line:84%
You just got a project funded
about the psychomanteum.

00:51:02.160 --> 00:51:03.340 align:middle line:90%
Can you tell me about that?

00:51:03.340 --> 00:51:04.310 align:middle line:90%
>>SCHLITZ: Sure.

00:51:04.310 --> 00:51:06.730 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, we're very
excited about it.

00:51:06.730 --> 00:51:09.330 align:middle line:84%
The psychomanteum
is a technique that

00:51:09.330 --> 00:51:11.370 align:middle line:90%
was developed by Raymond Moody.

00:51:11.370 --> 00:51:15.540 align:middle line:84%
And it comes out of the
ancient Greek culture,

00:51:15.540 --> 00:51:17.580 align:middle line:90%
where they would do scrying.

00:51:17.580 --> 00:51:21.300 align:middle line:84%
They would take a highly
polished surface or reflective

00:51:21.300 --> 00:51:25.860 align:middle line:84%
surface and they would do a
kind of divination practice

00:51:25.860 --> 00:51:30.000 align:middle line:84%
by looking and seeing if there
are patterns that emerge there.

00:51:30.000 --> 00:51:32.040 align:middle line:84%
Well, Moody was interested
in the possibility

00:51:32.040 --> 00:51:35.010 align:middle line:84%
that we could bring
that into a modern kind

00:51:35.010 --> 00:51:36.690 align:middle line:90%
of clinical environment.

00:51:36.690 --> 00:51:38.610 align:middle line:84%
And so he created
this situation where

00:51:38.610 --> 00:51:44.050 align:middle line:84%
you go into a fully darkened
room that has a mirror,

00:51:44.050 --> 00:51:47.370 align:middle line:84%
and there's a slight
illumination on the mirror.

00:51:47.370 --> 00:51:51.150 align:middle line:84%
So you're sitting there in
this room with your eyes open.

00:51:51.150 --> 00:51:53.940 align:middle line:84%
And our brains are
trained to see things

00:51:53.940 --> 00:51:55.420 align:middle line:90%
if your eyes are open.

00:51:55.420 --> 00:51:59.520 align:middle line:84%
But if they're not, we
start to create things.

00:51:59.520 --> 00:52:02.280 align:middle line:84%
And so this altered
state of consciousness

00:52:02.280 --> 00:52:06.340 align:middle line:84%
happens in the context of
the sensory deprivation.

00:52:06.340 --> 00:52:09.030 align:middle line:84%
So I don't have my
normal sensory input

00:52:09.030 --> 00:52:12.750 align:middle line:90%
and I am in a quiet space.

00:52:12.750 --> 00:52:19.230 align:middle line:84%
And people start to see
and hear voices or things--

00:52:19.230 --> 00:52:21.240 align:middle line:90%
little, wispy things.

00:52:21.240 --> 00:52:23.230 align:middle line:84%
They describe all
kinds of things.

00:52:23.230 --> 00:52:26.640 align:middle line:84%
And what you can
do is prime them,

00:52:26.640 --> 00:52:29.730 align:middle line:84%
prior to going into
the psychomanteum,

00:52:29.730 --> 00:52:34.830 align:middle line:84%
to touch base with
somebody that is departed.

00:52:34.830 --> 00:52:37.290 align:middle line:84%
Is there someone that
you always wanted

00:52:37.290 --> 00:52:41.430 align:middle line:84%
to have that final conversation
with but were never able to?

00:52:41.430 --> 00:52:46.980 align:middle line:84%
And that's often a huge
source of grief, suffering.

00:52:46.980 --> 00:52:50.520 align:middle line:84%
And if you can then
be liberated from that

00:52:50.520 --> 00:52:52.980 align:middle line:84%
by having that
final conversation,

00:52:52.980 --> 00:52:57.690 align:middle line:84%
it has very measurable
positive effects on people,

00:52:57.690 --> 00:52:59.500 align:middle line:90%
on their psychologies.

00:52:59.500 --> 00:53:03.750 align:middle line:84%
So we wrote a proposal
to look at this

00:53:03.750 --> 00:53:06.130 align:middle line:84%
in the context of
virtual reality.

00:53:06.130 --> 00:53:09.300 align:middle line:84%
So people will come in and
they'll put the goggles on,

00:53:09.300 --> 00:53:11.640 align:middle line:84%
and they'll have a total
immersion experience

00:53:11.640 --> 00:53:14.040 align:middle line:90%
of being in the psychomanteum.

00:53:14.040 --> 00:53:15.610 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: With the person's face?

00:53:15.610 --> 00:53:17.610 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: No, it'll be
just the darkened space,

00:53:17.610 --> 00:53:19.215 align:middle line:90%
with a slight illumination.

00:53:19.215 --> 00:53:21.150 align:middle line:84%
But it's kind of mirrors,
but you don't ever

00:53:21.150 --> 00:53:22.890 align:middle line:90%
see your own reflection.

00:53:22.890 --> 00:53:25.900 align:middle line:84%
And you just see a tiny
little bit of illumination.

00:53:25.900 --> 00:53:28.740 align:middle line:84%
And so the idea is
to see if we can

00:53:28.740 --> 00:53:33.240 align:middle line:84%
help people to move through
that grief process, to engage

00:53:33.240 --> 00:53:38.550 align:middle line:84%
in experiences that lie
outside their normal, everyday

00:53:38.550 --> 00:53:41.970 align:middle line:84%
encounters, and
ultimately using this

00:53:41.970 --> 00:53:46.108 align:middle line:84%
for the benefit of their
psychological well-being.

00:53:46.108 --> 00:53:47.400 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Their grieving process.

00:53:47.400 --> 00:53:48.817 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: Their
grieving process.

00:53:48.817 --> 00:53:51.840 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, this was funded through
a small foundation in Portugal

00:53:51.840 --> 00:53:55.120 align:middle line:84%
called Be All Foundation, and
we are very grateful to them.

00:53:55.120 --> 00:53:57.120 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Do you think any
of that is imagination,

00:53:57.120 --> 00:53:59.010 align:middle line:84%
or is that important
for healing?

00:53:59.010 --> 00:54:02.340 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: In this case,
it's not ontological.

00:54:02.340 --> 00:54:04.680 align:middle line:84%
In other words, we're
not trying to prove

00:54:04.680 --> 00:54:08.820 align:middle line:84%
the reality of the spirits
in the psychomanteum,

00:54:08.820 --> 00:54:14.070 align:middle line:84%
we are attempting to
invite experiences

00:54:14.070 --> 00:54:16.060 align:middle line:90%
that benefit the person.

00:54:16.060 --> 00:54:19.140 align:middle line:84%
So it's really not about proving
the existence of the spirit

00:54:19.140 --> 00:54:22.140 align:middle line:84%
world it's really about
creating an environment where

00:54:22.140 --> 00:54:25.650 align:middle line:84%
people can access those
experiences noetically.

00:54:25.650 --> 00:54:29.280 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So a last conversation,
or an I love you, or a hug,

00:54:29.280 --> 00:54:30.390 align:middle line:90%
or a touch.

00:54:30.390 --> 00:54:34.520 align:middle line:84%
I mean, just a mental
touch that means closure.

00:54:34.520 --> 00:54:37.320 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: Or
anything, really, that

00:54:37.320 --> 00:54:42.390 align:middle line:84%
invites a sense of something
beyond just the physical.

00:54:42.390 --> 00:54:45.282 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Did you get this
funding through the Trans--

00:54:45.282 --> 00:54:47.490 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: The Institute of
Transpersonal Psychology.

00:54:47.490 --> 00:54:48.720 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Transpersonal
Psychology.

00:54:48.720 --> 00:54:49.520 align:middle line:90%
>>SCHLITZ: We did.

00:54:49.520 --> 00:54:52.170 align:middle line:84%
Well, the Be All grant
came through ITP.

00:54:52.170 --> 00:54:55.560 align:middle line:84%
So ITP was the first
graduate program

00:54:55.560 --> 00:54:59.400 align:middle line:84%
in the country to look at
transpersonal psychology.

00:54:59.400 --> 00:55:04.430 align:middle line:84%
Basically most psychology
is very behaviorist.

00:55:04.430 --> 00:55:08.100 align:middle line:84%
It's psychology
developed with Skinner,

00:55:08.100 --> 00:55:10.080 align:middle line:84%
and the little box,
and conditioning.

00:55:10.080 --> 00:55:15.720 align:middle line:84%
And there was this sense that
all experiences were basically

00:55:15.720 --> 00:55:20.430 align:middle line:84%
something that, if they had a
negative connotation or they

00:55:20.430 --> 00:55:22.820 align:middle line:84%
had an otherworldly
connotation--

00:55:22.820 --> 00:55:25.170 align:middle line:84%
the kind of things
we're talking about--

00:55:25.170 --> 00:55:30.870 align:middle line:84%
they were probably illusions,
delusions, psychosis,

00:55:30.870 --> 00:55:33.510 align:middle line:90%
and pathological.

00:55:33.510 --> 00:55:39.120 align:middle line:84%
So the people who started
ITP, Bob Frager in particular,

00:55:39.120 --> 00:55:40.410 align:middle line:90%
had been trained.

00:55:40.410 --> 00:55:42.180 align:middle line:90%
He got his PhD at Harvard.

00:55:42.180 --> 00:55:44.280 align:middle line:84%
And he felt like there
was something more

00:55:44.280 --> 00:55:47.490 align:middle line:84%
to these experiences, that
you can talk to people who've

00:55:47.490 --> 00:55:51.300 align:middle line:84%
had these transformations, and
it doesn't seem pathological,

00:55:51.300 --> 00:55:53.710 align:middle line:90%
it seems pretty healthy.

00:55:53.710 --> 00:55:58.330 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, it opens up to a
broader range of experiences.

00:55:58.330 --> 00:56:01.020 align:middle line:10%
So the idea was to create
kind of the fourth wave

00:56:01.020 --> 00:56:05.520 align:middle line:10%
of psychology, where
instead of only treating

00:56:05.520 --> 00:56:10.200 align:middle line:10%
people who have pathologies,
it's also working with people

00:56:10.200 --> 00:56:13.380 align:middle line:10%
who are perfectly
healthy and want to grow,

00:56:13.380 --> 00:56:15.390 align:middle line:10%
want to expand their awareness.

00:56:15.390 --> 00:56:16.520 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting, OK.

00:56:16.520 --> 00:56:19.260 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: And so it's
really imbued with this sense

00:56:19.260 --> 00:56:22.980 align:middle line:84%
of possibility, positivity,
kind of a precursor

00:56:22.980 --> 00:56:25.115 align:middle line:84%
to the positive
psychology movement.

00:56:25.115 --> 00:56:27.820 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And what kind of
classes or courses are there?

00:56:27.820 --> 00:56:30.870 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: So we have a
master's and PhD level.

00:56:30.870 --> 00:56:34.530 align:middle line:84%
People can study
either psychology

00:56:34.530 --> 00:56:37.110 align:middle line:84%
as a research and
educational program,

00:56:37.110 --> 00:56:38.460 align:middle line:90%
or clinical psychology.

00:56:38.460 --> 00:56:42.960 align:middle line:84%
So we're training people
who are clinicians to be

00:56:42.960 --> 00:56:47.310 align:middle line:84%
able to manage the
experiences of their clients

00:56:47.310 --> 00:56:50.610 align:middle line:84%
in a way that doesn't
want to medicate them.

00:56:50.610 --> 00:56:52.830 align:middle line:84%
In fact, it wants
to explore them

00:56:52.830 --> 00:56:55.070 align:middle line:90%
in ways that invite curiosity.

00:56:55.070 --> 00:56:55.980 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's safe.

00:56:55.980 --> 00:56:56.938 align:middle line:90%
>>SCHLITZ: That's safe.

00:56:56.938 --> 00:57:00.510 align:middle line:84%
So my students are
very interested in--

00:57:00.510 --> 00:57:03.420 align:middle line:84%
I've got one who's doing a
project on death awareness

00:57:03.420 --> 00:57:08.730 align:middle line:84%
and looking at physical
and psychological changes.

00:57:08.730 --> 00:57:11.250 align:middle line:84%
Right now, I'm really
interested in--

00:57:11.250 --> 00:57:13.280 align:middle line:84%
we talked about
aging a little bit--

00:57:13.280 --> 00:57:16.530 align:middle line:84%
I'm working with a
woman named Ellen She's

00:57:16.530 --> 00:57:18.670 align:middle line:90%
a psychologist at Harvard.

00:57:18.670 --> 00:57:21.450 align:middle line:84%
And she did a study,
years ago, where

00:57:21.450 --> 00:57:25.170 align:middle line:84%
she took men into
an environment where

00:57:25.170 --> 00:57:28.060 align:middle line:90%
they were 20 years earlier.

00:57:28.060 --> 00:57:32.950 align:middle line:84%
So she created a house that
had everything 20 years ago.

00:57:32.950 --> 00:57:36.930 align:middle line:84%
So the magazines were 20
years earlier, the television,

00:57:36.930 --> 00:57:41.250 align:middle line:84%
the lighting, the doorknobs,
the furniture, the clothing.

00:57:41.250 --> 00:57:44.400 align:middle line:84%
And they were instructed
to really live

00:57:44.400 --> 00:57:46.620 align:middle line:90%
like it was 20 years ago.

00:57:46.620 --> 00:57:48.960 align:middle line:84%
And she found that
people had very positive

00:57:48.960 --> 00:57:51.520 align:middle line:84%
psychological changes
as a result of that.

00:57:51.520 --> 00:57:53.700 align:middle line:84%
So now we're looking
at doing that--

00:57:53.700 --> 00:57:55.860 align:middle line:84%
again, using the
virtual reality,

00:57:55.860 --> 00:57:58.230 align:middle line:84%
instead of trying to
set up a physical space,

00:57:58.230 --> 00:58:03.100 align:middle line:84%
we can give them a full
immersion into an experience

00:58:03.100 --> 00:58:04.440 align:middle line:90%
20 years earlier.

00:58:04.440 --> 00:58:07.300 align:middle line:84%
Or in the case of someone
with breast cancer,

00:58:07.300 --> 00:58:10.510 align:middle line:84%
for example, we can take them
10 years into the future.

00:58:10.510 --> 00:58:11.760 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Where they're healthy.

00:58:11.760 --> 00:58:13.680 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: Where they're
healthy, they're alive,

00:58:13.680 --> 00:58:15.138 align:middle line:84%
they're living to
see the new year.

00:58:15.138 --> 00:58:17.370 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's so
missing in health care,

00:58:17.370 --> 00:58:19.490 align:middle line:90%
is forward pacing the patient.

00:58:19.490 --> 00:58:20.290 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:58:20.290 --> 00:58:23.430 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: So it's kind of
turning some of our assumptions

00:58:23.430 --> 00:58:26.520 align:middle line:84%
on their heads, asking
questions in a different way,

00:58:26.520 --> 00:58:30.810 align:middle line:84%
trying to empower the
culture, reduce the suffering,

00:58:30.810 --> 00:58:33.720 align:middle line:84%
and ultimately expand
our human potentials.

00:58:33.720 --> 00:58:36.220 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Is this what you
did when you were at IONS?

00:58:36.220 --> 00:58:37.020 align:middle line:90%
>>SCHLITZ: Sure.

00:58:37.020 --> 00:58:42.300 align:middle line:84%
I've been working in this
field since I was about 20--

00:58:42.300 --> 00:58:44.580 align:middle line:90%
just yesterday.

00:58:44.580 --> 00:58:46.860 align:middle line:84%
And I have been
very interested--

00:58:46.860 --> 00:58:50.910 align:middle line:84%
since that out-of-body
experience on the motorcycle,

00:58:50.910 --> 00:58:53.700 align:middle line:84%
I have really been
interested in seeing

00:58:53.700 --> 00:58:57.370 align:middle line:90%
if we can't change the world.

00:58:57.370 --> 00:59:00.660 align:middle line:84%
And I began to really
understand that consciousness

00:59:00.660 --> 00:59:02.340 align:middle line:90%
may be the gateway.

00:59:02.340 --> 00:59:06.480 align:middle line:84%
And I started by working at the
Institute for Parapsychology

00:59:06.480 --> 00:59:08.380 align:middle line:90%
in Durham, North Carolina.

00:59:08.380 --> 00:59:11.140 align:middle line:84%
I went from there to
San Antonio, Texas

00:59:11.140 --> 00:59:13.560 align:middle line:84%
and worked at the Mind
Science Foundation.

00:59:13.560 --> 00:59:15.660 align:middle line:84%
There, I did a
series of experiments

00:59:15.660 --> 00:59:18.420 align:middle line:84%
with psychologist
William Braud, where

00:59:18.420 --> 00:59:20.500 align:middle line:84%
we were looking
at psychic healing

00:59:20.500 --> 00:59:22.110 align:middle line:84%
and we were looking
at the possibility

00:59:22.110 --> 00:59:25.320 align:middle line:84%
that one person's
intention could influence

00:59:25.320 --> 00:59:28.170 align:middle line:84%
the physiology of another
person at a distance,

00:59:28.170 --> 00:59:31.080 align:middle line:90%
and under random conditions.

00:59:31.080 --> 00:59:34.350 align:middle line:84%
And we found, after
14 formal experiments,

00:59:34.350 --> 00:59:38.370 align:middle line:84%
that there were significant
differences in the physiology

00:59:38.370 --> 00:59:43.050 align:middle line:84%
of the distant person when
the intention was directed

00:59:43.050 --> 00:59:44.430 align:middle line:90%
toward them from a distance.

00:59:44.430 --> 00:59:46.340 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So as a
parent, you could--

00:59:46.340 --> 00:59:48.090 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: Potentially
with a parent, yes.

00:59:48.090 --> 00:59:49.548 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: As a parent,
you could hope

00:59:49.548 --> 00:59:52.170 align:middle line:84%
for healing if you have a child
that's sick or lost their way.

00:59:52.170 --> 00:59:54.300 align:middle line:90%
>>SCHLITZ: Exactly-- or anyone.

00:59:54.300 --> 00:59:57.000 align:middle line:84%
And then we continued to
do some of that research

00:59:57.000 --> 01:00:01.150 align:middle line:84%
when I went to Science
Applications International

01:00:01.150 --> 01:00:01.950 align:middle line:90%
Corporation.

01:00:01.950 --> 01:00:04.140 align:middle line:84%
I worked at the
cognitive sciences lab.

01:00:04.140 --> 01:00:06.720 align:middle line:84%
That was the
government-sponsored program

01:00:06.720 --> 01:00:08.685 align:middle line:90%
from the DIA/CIA.

01:00:08.685 --> 01:00:10.810 align:middle line:84%
And then I went to the
Institute of Noetic Sciences

01:00:10.810 --> 01:00:12.660 align:middle line:90%
and spent 25 years there.

01:00:12.660 --> 01:00:15.180 align:middle line:84%
I don't know how that could
be just yesterday, but--

01:00:15.180 --> 01:00:16.250 align:middle line:90%
this time travel thing.

01:00:16.250 --> 01:00:17.942 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's that
grateful aging thing.

01:00:17.942 --> 01:00:19.630 align:middle line:90%
That works.

01:00:19.630 --> 01:00:22.150 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: And we looked at
all kinds of things there.

01:00:22.150 --> 01:00:24.300 align:middle line:84%
And one study in
particular stands out,

01:00:24.300 --> 01:00:28.960 align:middle line:84%
where we recruited couples,
one of whom had cancer,

01:00:28.960 --> 01:00:32.410 align:middle line:84%
and we took the healthy
partner through what

01:00:32.410 --> 01:00:35.530 align:middle line:84%
we call a compassionate
intention training program.

01:00:35.530 --> 01:00:38.320 align:middle line:84%
So oftentimes, when you
are in a relationship

01:00:38.320 --> 01:00:40.780 align:middle line:84%
and your partner
is suffering, you

01:00:40.780 --> 01:00:44.320 align:middle line:84%
can feel very disempowered,
like what can I do to help?

01:00:44.320 --> 01:00:45.318 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, helpless.

01:00:45.318 --> 01:00:47.360 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: So we took them
through this training.

01:00:47.360 --> 01:00:49.690 align:middle line:84%
They went home and
continued to practice.

01:00:49.690 --> 01:00:52.600 align:middle line:84%
And then we brought
them into the lab,

01:00:52.600 --> 01:00:54.550 align:middle line:84%
and we put them
in separate rooms.

01:00:54.550 --> 01:00:57.250 align:middle line:84%
And we had a video
camera on one person,

01:00:57.250 --> 01:01:00.340 align:middle line:84%
and a closed-circuit television
screen in the other room.

01:01:00.340 --> 01:01:02.980 align:middle line:84%
So they were physically,
sensorally separated

01:01:02.980 --> 01:01:04.300 align:middle line:90%
from each other.

01:01:04.300 --> 01:01:08.050 align:middle line:84%
And we monitored the
physiology of both people.

01:01:08.050 --> 01:01:12.370 align:middle line:84%
So when the healthy
partner was sending

01:01:12.370 --> 01:01:15.970 align:middle line:84%
loving, compassionate
intention to their partner,

01:01:15.970 --> 01:01:18.370 align:middle line:84%
you could see a
measurable change

01:01:18.370 --> 01:01:20.440 align:middle line:90%
in that person's physiology.

01:01:20.440 --> 01:01:24.130 align:middle line:84%
But interestingly, we
saw parallel changes

01:01:24.130 --> 01:01:25.700 align:middle line:90%
in both people.

01:01:25.700 --> 01:01:30.580 align:middle line:84%
So you might expect, if I'm
sending, willfully, something,

01:01:30.580 --> 01:01:32.920 align:middle line:84%
that I'm going to
show an arousal.

01:01:32.920 --> 01:01:36.340 align:middle line:84%
But it doesn't make sense
in the conventional model

01:01:36.340 --> 01:01:40.420 align:middle line:84%
that you would pick up on
that arousal at a distance.

01:01:40.420 --> 01:01:43.167 align:middle line:84%
But we did find that, to a
highly significant degree.

01:01:43.167 --> 01:01:44.000 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Fascinating.

01:01:44.000 --> 01:01:45.750 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: So we call
that the love study.

01:01:45.750 --> 01:01:48.820 align:middle line:84%
And I think it has really
powerful implications

01:01:48.820 --> 01:01:50.590 align:middle line:84%
for understanding
our entanglement

01:01:50.590 --> 01:01:51.715 align:middle line:90%
and our interconnectedness.

01:01:51.715 --> 01:01:54.720 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes,
relationships, completely.

01:01:54.720 --> 01:01:58.450 align:middle line:84%
A question for you-- why
do you do all that you do?

01:01:58.450 --> 01:01:59.470 align:middle line:90%
Tell me.

01:01:59.470 --> 01:02:02.620 align:middle line:84%
>>SCHLITZ: What
else is there to do?

01:02:02.620 --> 01:02:05.320 align:middle line:84%
I really can't
totally answer that.

01:02:05.320 --> 01:02:07.780 align:middle line:84%
I was telling somebody
about this new experiment

01:02:07.780 --> 01:02:09.550 align:middle line:84%
with the psychomanteum,
and they're

01:02:09.550 --> 01:02:12.887 align:middle line:84%
like, you really did find
a unique niche, didn't you?

01:02:12.887 --> 01:02:14.350 align:middle line:90%
[CHUCKLING]

01:02:14.350 --> 01:02:16.020 align:middle line:10%
It's just a curiosity.

01:02:16.020 --> 01:02:20.260 align:middle line:10%
I believe that the
world needs healing.

01:02:20.260 --> 01:02:24.920 align:middle line:10%
And I believe that there
are various ways to do that.

01:02:24.920 --> 01:02:27.340 align:middle line:10%
I think there's a lot of good
things that are happening.

01:02:27.340 --> 01:02:29.890 align:middle line:10%
But if we could
really begin to switch

01:02:29.890 --> 01:02:33.610 align:middle line:10%
how we hold our consciousness,
how we direct our consciousness

01:02:33.610 --> 01:02:35.800 align:middle line:10%
and intention
toward others, that

01:02:35.800 --> 01:02:38.590 align:middle line:10%
could be a recipe for success.

01:02:38.590 --> 01:02:39.980 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah, that is true.

01:02:39.980 --> 01:02:40.780 align:middle line:90%
I believe so.

01:02:40.780 --> 01:02:42.555 align:middle line:90%
It's a more conscious world.

01:02:42.555 --> 01:02:43.930 align:middle line:84%
